WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6.0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
I'm Neil.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Beth.

6
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:21.000
In this program, we're discussing the positives and negatives of social media in the lives of young people.

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:27.000
And this is a really trending topic at the moment because of what's happening in Australia,

8
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:34.000
where we're new law to limit under 16-year-olds access to social media is being debated.

9
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Neil, tell me, one good thing and one bad thing about having social media in your life.

10
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Well, one good thing is it means I can see what friends are doing who live far away.

11
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And one bad thing is it's really addictive and a massive waste of time.

12
00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:00.000
Well, it's interesting to hear a man's perspective, Neil, because when it comes to issues like cyberbullying,

13
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
it's often young women who are most affected.

14
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.000
So soon we'll be hearing from women in different countries about their online experiences.

15
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And remember, you can find all the vocabulary and a worksheet on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com.

16
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
But first, I have a question for you, Beth.

17
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:25.000
In 2024, which was the most regularly used social media platform in the world?

18
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Was it a, Facebook, B, Instagram, or C, TikTok?

19
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Oh, I'm going to say TikTok.

20
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Well, we'll find out the answer at the end of the program.

21
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Now, let's start with the positive side of social media.

22
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:43.000
As a politics student at Oklahoma University,

23
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
21-year-old Hayley Hurst campaigned in the 2024 US presidential election.

24
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Here, she explains one benefit of social media to BBC World Service program Pick of the World.

25
00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:02.000
I do think social media has played a huge role in educating young voters on different policies and different people who are running.

26
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
I know Trump has recently said that he has a soft spot in his heart for TikTok.

27
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.000
With the growth of social media, it has sparked a lot more debates.

28
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:16.000
I think my generation too has seen so many climactic things happen.

29
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Hayley thinks one good thing about social media is that it sparks debates and conversations.

30
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.000
It causes debates to start.

31
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:32.000
She comments that Donald Trump is a fan of social media by saying he has a soft spot for TikTok.

32
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:38.000
If you have a soft spot for something or someone, you feel affectionate and fond of it.

33
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:39.000
You like it a lot.

34
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
But of course, that's not the whole story.

35
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Increasingly, young women are reporting the negative impact social media is making on their lives.

36
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.000
And the pressure they feel to appear perfect online, especially for men.

37
00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:01.000
Manbijshama age 28 is a businesswoman and model with a large Instagram following who lives in Delhi, India.

38
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:07.000
And Kemi Adyemi is a 26 year old travel blogger from Lagos in Nigeria.

39
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Both young women discuss these social media worries with BBC World Service program Pick of the World.

40
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
The person you're dating, they might leave you just because of the social media.

41
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
I think that you're not good for marriage.

42
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:27.000
You can be a good partner because you're social media because you're being watched by a lot of people.

43
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.000
And they feel a little intimidated by this.

44
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:31.000
You know what?

45
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.000
We saw your girlfriend when she was wearing this.

46
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Oh, my God.

47
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.000
But it's affecting my personal life.

48
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Some men or some people don't just shrink yourself so that they can like be the bigger person.

49
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
They get to listen to what you're afraid to say about you or your family says about you.

50
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And they're not able to like stand up for you to say, oh, I know this person.

51
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.000
I believe she's not like doing this thing for all our reasons.

52
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:03.000
Manbijshama thinks some men are intimidated by her popularity on Instagram.

53
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Intimidated means to feel frightened or nervous because you lack confidence.

54
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:14.000
She feels people gossip about her posts and photos using expressions like, oh my gosh.

55
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
And oh my God, to express their shock or surprise.

56
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
And Kemi agrees.

57
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
She says that on social media, some people want her to shrink herself.

58
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:33.000
A phrase meaning that you underuse your full potential in order to avoid making people feel uncomfortable or to fit in.

59
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:38.000
When she's bullied online, Kemi says that these people don't stand up for her.

60
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
To stand up for someone means to defend or support someone who's being criticised.

61
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Or bullied.

62
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And I think it's time you reveal the answer to your question, Neil.

63
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:55.000
I asked which was the most regularly used social media platform in the world in 2024.

64
00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Facebook, Instagram, or TikTok. What did you say, Beth?

65
00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:00.000
TikTok.

66
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:01.000
I'm afraid you're wrong.

67
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.000
It's Facebook with over 3 billion regular users.

68
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Okay, let's recap to the vocabulary we've learned in this program,

69
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:15.000
starting with the verb spark, meaning to call something such as a debate or argument to start happening.

70
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:21.000
If you have a soft spot for someone, you feel affection for them. You like them very much.

71
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:27.000
To be intimidated means to feel frightened or nervous because you lack confidence in a situation.

72
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:36.000
The expressions, oh my gosh, and oh my God, are exclamation of strong feelings like shock, surprise, anger or disbelief.

73
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:45.000
If you shrink yourself, you make yourself smaller and don't use your full potential in order to make others feel comfortable or to fit in with them.

74
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And finally, to stand up for someone means to be vocal in defending a person who is being bullied.

75
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Once again, our time is up, but if you're ready for more head over to the BBC Learning English website

76
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.000
to try the worksheet with a quiz for this program. See you there soon.

77
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Goodbye.

78
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
6.0 English

79
00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:09.000
From BBC LearningEnglish.com
